{"text": ["The details are finely worked out; the repose proper to hair in a recumbent and inactive attitude is charmingly expressed.", "There is a feeling about this part of the work which lifts it to the highest altitudes of art; the sense of sordid realism vanishes away--one recognizes that there is SOUL here.", "View this Trunk as you will, it is a gem, it is a marvel, it is a miracle.", "Some of the effects are very daring, approaching even to the boldest flights of the rococo, the sirocco, and the Byzantine schools--yet the master's hand never falters--it moves on, calm, majestic, confident--and, with that art which conceals art, it finally casts over the TOUT ENSEMBLE, by mysterious methods of its own, a subtle something which refines, subdues, etherealizes the arid components and endures them with the deep charm and gracious witchery of poesy.", "Among the art-treasures of Europe there are pictures which approach the Hair Trunk--there are two which may be said to equal it, possibly--but there is none that surpasses it."], "style": "<MT>", "title": "A_TRAMP_ABROAD"}
