{"text": ["They got a special charter from the legislature, with large powers, under the name of the Pilots' Benevolent Association; elected their officers, completed their organization, contributed capital, put 'association' wages up to two hundred and fifty dollars at once--and then retired to their homes, for they were promptly discharged from employment.", "But there were two or three unnoticed trifles in their by-laws which had the seeds of propagation in them.", "For instance, all idle members of the association, in good standing, were entitled to a pension of twenty-five dollars per month.", "This began to bring in one straggler after another from the ranks of the new-fledged pilots, in the dull (summer) season.", "Better have twenty-five dollars than starve; the initiation fee was only twelve dollars, and no dues required from the unemployed."], "style": "<MT>", "title": "Life on the Mississippi"}
{"text": ["Also, the widows of deceased members in good standing could draw twenty-five dollars per month, and a certain sum for each of their children.", "Also, the said deceased would be buried at the association's expense.", "These things resurrected all the superannuated and forgotten pilots in the Mississippi Valley.", "They came from farms, they came from interior villages, they came from everywhere."], "style": "<MT>", "title": "Life on the Mississippi"}
