{"text": ["I was on board the first boat that tried to go through the cut-off at American Bend, but we did not get through.", "It was toward midnight, and a wild night it was--thunder, lightning, and torrents of rain.", "It was estimated that the current in the cut-off was making about fifteen or twenty miles an hour; twelve or thirteen was the best our boat could do, even in tolerably slack water, therefore perhaps we were foolish to try the cut-off.", "However, Mr. Brown was ambitious, and he kept on trying.", "The eddy running up the bank, under the 'point,' was about as swift as the current out in the middle; so we would go flying up the shore like a lightning express train, get on a big head of steam, and 'stand by for a surge' when we struck the current that was whirling by the point."], "style": "<MT>", "title": "Life on the Mississippi"}
